elf or a neo-Epicurean. Chapter 4 focuses on Lucretius’ own additions to the material he derived from his sources and on his poetical and rhetorical contributions, which were extensive. Lucretius shows an understanding of philosophical points by adapting his poetical devices to the philosophical arguments. Chapter 4 also argues that Lucretius anticipates philosophical points in what have often been regarded as the ‘purple passages’ of his poem - e.g. the invocation of Venus in the proem, and the description of Sicily and Aetna - so that he could take them up later on in his narrative and provide an adequate explanation of reality.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aDoxographie. 4aEpikur. 4aLukrez. 4aPapyri aus Herculaneum. 4aRezeption der Vorsokratiker. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aDoxography.  aEpicurus.  aHerculaneum Papyri.  aLucretius.  aReception of Presocratics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Philosophy 2000-2014 (EN)z978311023848808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Philosophy 2000 - 2014z9783110636949oZDB-23-GPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE CLASSICAL STUDIES 2012z9783110293838oZDB-23-DGD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET ALTERTUM 2012z9783110288964oZDB-23-DGD0 cprintz978311019452440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311021881740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110218817423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110218817/original  a978-3-11-023848-8  DGBA B